WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:09.200
<v Speaker 1>An interesting thing about prepositions is that they have a habit of changing between languages.

00:00:08.940 --> 00:00:14.940
<v Speaker 1>To give you an example, in English we say I fall in love with.

00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:19.820
<v Speaker 1>In Spanish you say I enamor myself of

00:00:20.539 --> 00:00:24.060
<v Speaker 1>I fall in love of you.

00:00:24.060 --> 00:00:31.419
<v Speaker 1>Now, again, this is something that we look at with interest rather than looking at it as an obstacle.

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:41.560
<v Speaker 1>for the insight that it might give us about how we perceive and express the world through our own language.

00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:46.120
<v Speaker 1>Now the fact that we use with is not necessarily casual.

00:00:46.120 --> 00:00:48.360
<v Speaker 1>Casual in the sense of meaningless.

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:52.440
<v Speaker 1>The fact that we use with is not necessarily without its weight

00:00:52.340 --> 00:00:53.460
<v Speaker 1>without its meaning.

00:00:53.460 --> 00:01:05.379
<v Speaker 1>If I say I fall in love with you, that preposition with necessarily involves you in my process of falling in love.

00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:10.680
<v Speaker 1>Now this of is much more detached in feeling than with.

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:13.080
<v Speaker 1>So there is a school of thought

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:21.520
<v Speaker 1>Which explores how these elements of language might have a real tangible effect on the way we interact.

00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:28.840
<v Speaker 1>with the world and with certain concepts and the way we express them and how that feeds back into the way we perceive and view the world.

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:35.000
<v Speaker 1>And I think this is a very nice example between falling in love with and falling in love of

00:01:35.620 --> 00:01:45.940
<v Speaker 1>So this is something to think about and just take interest in whenever you find that in Spanish the verb uses a different preposition than the one it does in English.

00:01:45.540 --> 00:01:53.220
<v Speaker 1>rather than just seeing it as a hurdle to correctness that you need to memorize, maybe have a little look at how

00:01:53.460 --> 00:01:58.740
<v Speaker 1>it might actually be affecting somehow or other the way you perceive the world.

00:01:58.740 --> 00:02:01.380
<v Speaker 1>This also helps the memory on a practical level.

00:02:01.380 --> 00:02:05.700
<v Speaker 1>You are much more capable of internalizing and remembering

00:02:05.860 --> 00:02:17.060
<v Speaker 1>this difference if rather than just mindlessly memorizing that you're using de instead of con here, we are looking more with a more analytical eye

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:23.000
<v Speaker 1>with a curious eye to understand the what effect this might possibly have on us.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.000
<v Speaker 1>And in this way we're just gonna learn the differences much easier.

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:29.200
<v Speaker 1>Let's start with this verb.

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:32.400
<v Speaker 1>To fall in love is to enamor oneself.

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:38.560
<v Speaker 1>So if you look up in the dictionary to fall in love, what you will find is enamorarse.

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:39.800
<v Speaker 1>Written as one word.

00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:42.120
<v Speaker 1>Now it's important to realize that it's not one word.

00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:48.599
<v Speaker 1>You still have a verb there ending are and amorar, and then the se is just hooked on

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:51.160
<v Speaker 1>So let's start with I fall in love.

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:55.800
<v Speaker 1>How will you make enamorar say I fall in love?

00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:57.560
<v Speaker 1>I enamor myself

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:00.060
<v Speaker 2>Me enamoro.

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:00.620
<v Speaker 1>Exactly.

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:01.980
<v Speaker 1>Me enamoro.

00:03:01.980 --> 00:03:07.180
<v Speaker 1>Now if you want to say I fall in love with you, we're probably gonna speak informally.

00:03:07.180 --> 00:03:09.980
<v Speaker 1>In Spanish, we're not gonna say with you, we're gonna say

00:03:10.599 --> 00:03:11.640
<v Speaker 1>of you.

00:03:11.640 --> 00:03:15.000
<v Speaker 1>I enamor myself of you.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.040
<v Speaker 2>Me enamoro de ti.

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:18.680
<v Speaker 1>Yeah.

00:03:18.680 --> 00:03:20.519
<v Speaker 1>Me enamoro de ti.

